06423nam a22010215i 9781853599682DE-B159720211217065530.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211217t20072007enk    fo  d z      eng d  a2007000093  a97818535996827 a10.21832/97818535996822doi  a(DE-B1597)513533  a(OCoLC)1078919264  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aenkcGB-BST00aP118.2b.S4356 2007 4aP118.2b.S4356 2007 7aLAN0090402bisacsh04a401 .9322200aSecond Language Lexical Processes :bApplied Linguistic and Psycholinguistic Perspectives /ced. by Zsolt Lengyel, Judit Navracsics. 1aBristol ;aBlue Ridge Summit : bMultilingual Matters, c[2007] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (176 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSecond Language Acquisition0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe book contains studies on second language lexical processes based on empirical findings by authors mostly from Central Europe. The reader may have access to how lexical items are stored in the memory and also to how second language lexicons work in speech processing. Questions of the two lexicons’ integration or separation, the fashion of bilingual word storage, vocabulary acquisition and assessment, word retrieval from the memory and lexical access are the focus of the studies. The authors of the studies refer to analyses of different psycholinguistic experiments (e.g. a word association test, speech perception tests, a Cloze-test). Assessment of written work of second language learners both at secondary school and university levels is also provided. Second language lexical acquisition processes are described and the influences of different types of languages on each other are shown. The second languages involved are mainly internationally less widely investigated and published languages of Finno-Ugric (i.e. Hungarian) and Indo-European (e.g. Croatian, Polish, Russian, etc.) origin next to the more frequently studied English and German. The studies included in our volume focus on lexical acquisition and processing and also make reference to pedagogical questions. They include investigations of lexical perception, production, acquisitional processes and vocabulary assessment. The novelty of the book is that the studies make reference to Hungarian and a number of Slavic languages. They provide the reader with new perspectives on second language lexical acquisition processes when the source language and the target language are distinct from a typological point of view, the lexicon in processing terms. The book is intended for the use of undergraduate and graduate students of second language studies, psycholinguistics and/or bilingualism researchers, teachers and academics whose interests include a second language acquisition component.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aLexicologyxPsychological aspects. 0aLexicologyxPsycological aspects. 0aSecond langage acquisition. 0aSecond language acquisition. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / Psycholinguistics.2bisacsh  aL2 lexical processes.  aL2 processing.  aSLA.  aSecond Language Acquisition.  alearning vocab.  alexical access.  alexical acquisition.  alexicon.  amemory.  apsycholinguistics.  asecond language lexical processes.  avocabulary acquisition.1 aCvikić, Lidija, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDoró, Katalin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGergely, Zsuzsanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGósy, Mária, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeresztes, Csilla, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLengyel, Zsolt, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.go